data.content:
Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`. Both compile and run without issues. On this 64-bit system, `nint` is 8 bytes. The syntax is straightforward:

```csharp
Span<nint> span = stackalloc nint[5];
Span<nuint> uspan = stackalloc nuint[3];
```

This has been supported since C# 9 / .NET 5 when `nint`/`nuint` were introduced as first-class types (aliases for `IntPtr`/`UIntPtr`). They're valid `unmanaged` types, so they satisfy the `stackalloc` constraint.
